<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP FACES: ZHANE; HEY, MR. DEEJAY, DON'T PIGEONHOLE THEM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DENNIS HUNT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 If you want to see Renee Neufville and Jean Norris -- the vocal duo Zhane -- 
do a slow burn, call them terrific dance-music artists and predict they'll have 
more dance-oriented hits like the Top 5 "Hey Mr. D.J." 
</P>
<P>
 "We're not dance-music artists," Neufville insists. 
</P>
<P>
 As evidence, she offers their debut album, "Pronounced Jah-Nay." "There's a 
variety of material on it -- R&B, jazz and some hip-hop," she says. "Also, we 
write our own material, we can really sing and we're schooled in music -- Jean 
even majored in music in college. For us, dance music is a steppingstone to 
something bigger." 
</P>
<P>
 So how do they explain their current single, "Groove Thang" -- another 
danceable tune? 
</P>
<P>
 "There had to be a transition song," Norris says. "It was written for the fans 
who expect the same kind of song as 'Mr. D.J.' " 
</P>
<P>
 Norris, who's from Moorestown, N.J., and Brooklyn native Neufville -- both 23 
-- met as freshmen at Philadelphia's Temple University. While working on their 
degrees (both graduated last year) they moonlighted as performers and looked 
for a record deal. By 1991, their biggest credit was singing background on the 
DJ Jazzy Jeff & the Fresh Prince single "Ring My Bell." Says Neufville: "It was 
fun but it didn't really lead to anything." 
</P>
<P>
 What did lead to something was landing "Hey Mr. D.J." on last year's 
compilation album "Roll Wit' Tha Flava." The song was eventually released as a 
single, and its success generated a bidding war for Zhane (a blend of the 
pair's first names), which Motown won. Explaining why the label signed the duo, 
label President and CEO Jheryl Busby says: "They're excellent songwriters and 
singers, and they're in the tradition of the great Motown acts." 
</P>
<P>
 "Everybody wants to be taken seriously," Neufville says. "Everybody wants 
respect and nobody wants to be pigeonholed or regarded as limited -- certainly 
not with your first hit. We're well-rounded artists. Some of the dance artists 
are here today and gone tomorrow. That's not us."DENNIS HUNT 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Profile 
</P>
