<P>
COLLEGE ROUNDUP; SEVEN-RUN SEVENTH LEADS FULLERTON TO EIGHTH VICTORY IN A ROW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Cal State Fullerton scored seven runs in the seventh inning Saturday en route 
to an 11-6 nonconference college baseball victory over Texas at Austin, 
extending the sixth-ranked Titans' winning streak to eighth. 
</P>
<P>
 Jim Betzsold hit his third home run and D.C. Olsen his second to lead a 15-hit 
Fullerton attack. Third baseman Craig Skyberg had three hits, two runs scored 
and a run batted in, and second baseman Jeff Ferguson had two hits, two RBIs 
and two runs scored. 
</P>
<P>
 Chad Rolish (2-1) pitched 5 1/3 innings, giving up two runs on two hits, 
walking one and striking out three. Derek Fahs and Ted Silva combined to shut 
out the No. 8 Longhorns (6-2) over the last 1 2/3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
 Fullerton (9-1) will try to sweep Texas for the first time, when the teams 
conclude the series today. 
</P>
<P>
 In other nonconference baseball: 
</P>
<P>
 Azusa Pacific 8, Chapman 5 -- Mike Regan was two for five with a double and 
two RBIs, and Juan Hernandez recorded the victory in relief for Azusa Pacific 
(5-0). Kurt Towsen was two for five with a double and a triple for Chapman 
(0-3-1). 
</P>
<P>
 Cal State Dominquez Hills 2, Southern California College 1 -- Cal State 
Dominquez Hills scored on a two-out, bases-loaded walk in the eighth to beat 
SCC (0-4). 
</P>
<P>
 The Toros (3-2) were held hitless by Paul Gutierrez (0-2) until the eighth, 
when Jesse Espinoza led off with a single before scoring the winning run on a 
walk to Ray Judy. 
</P>
<P>
 In nonconference softball: 
</P>
<P>
 Southern California College 8-2, UC Riverside 1-3 -- Angie Vega went three for 
six with a double and a triple in the doubleheader for SCC (1-1). Shannon 
Saylor earned the victory in the first game. UC Riverside is 3-1. 
</P>
<P>
 In nonconference men's swimming: 
</P>
<P>
 UC Santa Barbara 147.5, UC Irvine 95.5 -- In freestyle races, Elijah Fan won 
the 200 (1 minute 46.29 seconds) and 500 (4:47.46) and Mark Swangel the 50 
(21.55) and 100 (48.01) for Irvine (2-12). 
</P>
<P>
