<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA ENROLLMENT MAY SWELL BY 200 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Spring enrollment at the Ventura campus of Cal State Northridge could rise by 
as many as 200 as students displaced from the earthquake-damaged classrooms at 
the college's main campus drive north for instruction, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 Classes are scheduled to begin Monday at the tiny Ventura satellite campus, 
but students can register for Ventura courses until March 4.Administrators 
expect an influx of 100 to 200 new students in addition to the approximately 
1,300 full- and part-time students the campus normally enrolls, said Joyce 
Kennedy, director of the Ventura site. 
</P>
<P>
 Several classes still have openings, and two additional business courses have 
been added to the schedule, Kennedy said. 
</P>
<P>
 Although classroom space and parking at the building on Allesandro Drive have 
always been tight, the campus will be able to handle more students because the 
added classes will be taught during the day. Most Ventura campus classes are 
given at night, geared toward working adults pursuing upper-level classes to 
complete a degree. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
