<HEADLINE>
<P>
'94 WINTER OLYMPICS / LILLEHAMMER; SOME OF OTHER EVENTS BEAR WATCHING TOO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RANDY HARVEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Yes, America, there is more to the Winter Olympic figure skating competition 
than Tonya vs. Nancy. 
</P>
<P>
 A brief look: MEN 
</P>
<P>
 This will be the first time that two Olympic figure skating champions have 
faced one another. The United States' Brian Boitano won in 1988, Ukraine's 
Viktor Petrenko in 1992, and both enjoyed the spoils as professionals before 
the International Skating Union passed a rule enabling them to return to 
serious competition. The other leading contender is Canada's Kurt Browning, a 
four-time world champion. 
</P>
<P>
 Petrenko has emerged as the favorite, considering that neither Boitano nor 
Browning won his national championship this winter. Boitano, unable to fully 
recover from a knee injury, was second to Scott Davis. Browning finished behind 
Elvis Stojko. Elvis does live. PAIRS 
</P>
<P>
 It's a Russian intramural affair. And just like the Bolshoi vs. the Kirov, 
it's Moscow vs. St. Petersburg. The Muscovites, 1988 Olympic champions 
Ekaterina Gordeeva and Sergei Grinkov, appear to have the edge over Natalia 
Mishkutenok and Artur Dmitriev, the 1992 gold medalists. 
</P>
<P>
 The reigning world champions, Canadians Isabelle Brasseur and Lloyd Eisler, 
Russians Evgenia Shishkova and Vadim Naumov, Germans Mandy Wotzel and Ingo 
Steuer and Czechs Radka Kovarikova and Rene Novotny, who train at Lake 
Arrowhead, are medal contenders. So are U.S. champions Jenni Meno and Todd Sand 
of Costa Mesa, who could finish anywhere from third to seventh. Fifth place 
would be considered outstanding. DANCE 
</P>
<P>
 Ten years after they wowed the figure skating world with "Bolero" in winning 
the gold medal at Sarajevo, Great Britain's great Jayne Torvill and Christopher 
Dean are back. But they had some difficulty in their first major competition 
last month, barely winning the European championship ahead of two Russian 
teams, Oksana Gritschuk and Evgeny Platov, and Maia Usova and Alexander Zhulin. 
Expect another close decision. 
</P>
<P>
 The only U.S. team is Elizabeth Punsalan and Jerod Swallow, a married couple 
who will be competing two weeks after her father was stabbed to death by her 
brother. Competing so that they can take their family's mind off the tragedy, 
they would be satisfied with a top-10 finish. RANDY HARVEY 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA021394-0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 013229 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
February 13, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
